posts.raw_content:
They don’t get angry because you’re wrong. They get angry because you’ve violated the ritual.  
In radical belief systems, left, right, or otherwise, truth isn’t measured by correspondence to reality. It’s measured by moral resonance. Say something that contradicts their doctrine, and it’s not processed as   “disagreement”, it’s blasphemy.  
And blasphemy must be punished.  
But here’s the trick: they aren’t just defending an argument. They’re defending a fragile cognitive architecture, a belief system propped up by social validation, emotional certainty, and a deep need for moral superiority. Break any one pillar, and you don’t just provoke discomfort, you threaten ego identity.  
And that’s why mockery works.  
See, the prefrontal cortex handles reasoning, but social threats trigger the limbic system, especially the amygdala. A sarcastic meme doesn’t just “offend”, it hijacks. It tells the reader:  
"Not only is your belief ridiculous, I can make people laugh at it."
That’s more than disagreement. That’s status degradation. And in collective ideologies where identity is fused with cause, this feels like annihilation.  
So when a simple joke, say, “I identify as correct. My pronouns are told/you so.”, causes a meltdown, it’s not because it’s clever.  
It’s because it collapses the sacred with a smirk.  
And sacred things aren’t meant to be laughed at.  
Until they are.  
Then they fall.
